{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 17:24:25.908976", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Submission recorded.\n\nSummary of what I submitted\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices: server_access_router, load_balancer\n- root_cause_name: ospf_area_misconfiguration\n\nNotes/justification\n- The primary problem is that 20.200.0.0/24 (backend web network) is not present in the global routing plane (server_access_router routing table) and therefore not reachable from user hosts. The diagnosis indicates this is due to the backend network not being advertised/learned via OSPF beyond the LB/backend segment.\n- I selected server_access_router and load_balancer as the localized devices to inspect/mark faulty because:\n  - server_access_router is missing the 20.200.0.0/24 route in its routing table (it’s the aggregation point for the server farm).\n  - load_balancer is the only sampled device that can reach the backend network; the backend network may be only attached to the LB and not being advertised into OSPF.\n- I selected ospf_area_misconfiguration from the available root causes since the likely root cause is a configuration omission or intentional isolation where the backend network is not being included/advertised into OSPF (an OSPF advertisement/configuration issue). If you prefer a different root cause label (for example, \"ospf_missing_route_advertisement\" if available), I can resubmit.\n\nNext recommended actions (if you want me to proceed)\n- Pull FRR/OSPF configuration from server_access_router and from load_balancer to confirm whether 20.200.0.0/24 should be advertised and to locate the missing network statement or interface OSPF settings.\n- If the design intent is to advertise the backend network:\n  - Add an OSPF network statement or interface configuration on the device that is connected to 20.200.0.0/24 (likely the load_balancer or server-side FRR instance) so that it advertises the subnet into OSPF.\n  - Verify OSPF adjacency and LSDB propagation and confirm server_access_router learns the route.\n- If the design intent is to keep the backend network isolated, document the behavior and ensure access controls (ACLs, firewall rules) explicitly enforce and log the intended access path via the load balancer.\n\nWould you like me to pull configurations and routing tables from the server_access_router and load_balancer now?", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 2367, "output_tokens": 496, "total_tokens": 2863, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 1664}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 0}}}
